  "doc_id": "48818",
  "text": "The operations that initially give priority to an automated process are the start and stop services of the equipment, operations that detect defects, operations that add effort to the operator (such as loading or transport activities), and feeding operations. However, these concepts are not new because, in the eighteenth century, the Jidoka methodology emerged, which was initially called Autonomation. This method is very close to automation, and its objective was to provide intelligence to machines without the need for human supervision [CITATION_1] . However, as the fourth revolution advances, companies have understood that the human being is always necessary and the one that brings logic to the cognition of systems. Even if the automation is full, the system needs a previous configuration [20] .",
